import pandas as pd

# Reading dataset from its actual location
HPI = '/content/hpi_victoria.csv'
CPI = '/content/CPI_MONTHLY.csv'
INTR = '/content/interest_rate.csv'

# Read the CSV file into a pandas DataFrame
df1 = pd.read_csv(HPI)
df2 = pd.read_csv(CPI)
df2 = df2.rename(columns={'date': 'Date'})
df3 = pd.read_csv(INTR)
# Remove '%' sign and convert to numeric
df3['Prime Rate'] = df3['Prime Rate'].str.rstrip('%').astype('float') / 100.0
df3['Target for the Overnight Rate'] = df3['Target for the Overnight Rate'].str.rstrip('%').astype('float') / 100.0

# Sort the DataFrame based on the 'Date' column in ascending order
df1_sorted = df1.sort_values(by='Date')
df2_sorted = df2.sort_values(by='Date')
df3_sorted = df3.sort_values(by='Date')

# Sorted DataFrame back to the same CSV file with a consistent date format
df1_sorted.to_csv('/content/hpi_victoria.csv', index=False)
df2_sorted.to_csv('/content/CPI_MONTHLY.csv', index=False)
df3_sorted.to_csv('/content/interest_rate.csv', index=False)

# Print the sorted DataFrame
print(df1_sorted)
print(df2_sorted)
print(df3_sorted)

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
# Merge DataFrames based on 'Date' column and replace null with NaN'
merged_df = pd.merge(df1_sorted, df2_sorted, on='Date', how='outer')
merged_df = pd.merge(merged_df, df3_sorted, on='Date', how='outer')

# Replace NaN with 'null'
merged_df = merged_df.fillna('null')
merged_df.replace('null', np.nan, inplace=True)

# Print the merged DataFrame
print("After Merging all dataset")
print("--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------")
print(merged_df)
merged_sort= merged_df.sort_values(by='Date')
merged_sort.to_csv('/content/Merge_Data_Sorted.csv', index=False)
# Print the merged and sorted DataFrame
print("\n")
print("After sorting the merged dataset")
print("--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------")
print(merged_sort)

import pandas as pd
#For eliminating row which doesnot have any values majorly
merged_sort['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(merged_sort['Date'])

# Define the date range to eliminate
start_date = pd.to_datetime('01-01-1995')
end_date = pd.to_datetime('11-01-2007')

# Create a boolean mask to filter rows outside the specified date range
mask = (merged_sort['Date'] < start_date) | (merged_sort['Date'] > end_date)

# Apply the mask to eliminate rows within the specified date range
df = merged_sort[mask]
df.to_csv('/content/DATAFRAME.csv', index=False)
# Now, df contains only the rows outside the specified date range
print("THE dataset after eliminating null values")
print("---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------")
print(df)

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import tensorflow as tf
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.metrics import mean_absolute_error
from tensorflow.keras.callbacks import EarlyStopping, ModelCheckpoint
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load data
data = pd.read_csv("/content/final.csv")

# Extract features and target variable
X = data[['One_Storey_Benchmark_SA','Two_Storey_Benchmark_SA','Townhouse_Benchmark_SA', 'Apartment_Benchmark_SA', 'V41690973', 'V41690914',
          'STATIC_TOTALCPICHANGE','CPI_TRIM', 'CPI_MEDIAN', 'CPI_COMMON', 'ATOM_V41693242', 'STATIC_CPIXFET', 'CPIW','Prime Rate','Target for the Overnight Rate']]
y = data['Single_Family_Benchmark_SA']

# Standardize the features
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)

# Reshape data for CNN-LSTM
X_reshaped = X_scaled.reshape((X_scaled.shape[0], X_scaled.shape[1], 1))

# Split the data into training and testing sets
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_reshaped, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

# Define the CNN-LSTM model with two Conv1D layers
model = tf.keras.Sequential([
    tf.keras.layers.Conv1D(64, kernel_size=3, activation='relu', input_shape=(X_train.shape[1], 1)),
    tf.keras.layers.MaxPooling1D(pool_size=2),
    tf.keras.layers.Conv1D(32, kernel_size=3, activation='relu'),
    tf.keras.layers.MaxPooling1D(pool_size=2),
    tf.keras.layers.LSTM(50, activation='relu'),
    tf.keras.layers.Dense(32, activation='relu'),
    tf.keras.layers.Dense(1)
])

optimizer = tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.001)

# Compile the model
model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='mean_squared_error', metrics=['mae'])

# Set up callbacks for early stopping and model checkpoint
early_stopping = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', patience=10, restore_best_weights=True)
model_checkpoint = ModelCheckpoint('best_model.h5', monitor='val_loss', save_best_only=True)

# Train the model
history = model.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs=300, batch_size=32, validation_split=0.2, callbacks=[early_stopping, model_checkpoint])

# Load the best model
best_model = tf.keras.models.load_model('best_model.h5')

# Make predictions
predictions = best_model.predict(X_test)

def plot_learning_curve(history):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))

    # Plot training & validation MAE values
    plt.plot(history.history['mae'], label='Training MAE')
    plt.plot(history.history['val_mae'], label='Validation MAE')

    plt.title('Model MAE Learning Curve')
    plt.xlabel('Epoch')
    plt.ylabel('MAE')
    plt.legend()
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.show()

    # Plot training & validation loss values
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    plt.plot(history.history['loss'], label='Training Loss')
    plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'], label='Validation Loss')

    plt.title('Model Loss Learning Curve')
    plt.xlabel('Epoch')
    plt.ylabel('Loss')
    plt.legend()
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.show()

# Plot learning curves
plot_learning_curve(history)
